who 2025-08-13 06:32 p.m.
The Plaintiff has asked for

WHEREFORE, Plaintiff, the State of Mayflower, respectfully requests that this Court enter
judgment in its favor and against Defendants and grant the following relief:

a. Permanently enjoin Defendants, their officers, directors, members, managers, agents,
employees, affiliates, successors, and assigns from engaging in the fraudulent, illegal,
and racketeering conduct alleged herein.

b. Dissolve Defendant Columbia First Party and Defendant Meyerhauser Logging, LLC
pursuant to 4 M.S.C. 2 1204, and order the liquidation of their assets, with
distribution of proceeds as justice requires.

c. Appoint a receiver to take control of, manage, and oversee the winding down of
Defendants affairs, including the collection, preservation, and distribution of assets.
d. Order the seizure and forfeiture to the State of all assets, securities, funds, and
property derived from, or used in, the racketeering and illegal acts described herein,
pursuant to 4 M.S.C. 2 1205 and applicable law.

e. Award treble damages to the State of Mayflower for the injuries sustained as a result
of Defendants violations of the Mayflower RICO Act, pursuant to 4 M.S.C. 2
1206.

f. Award restitution to the State of Mayflower and its residents for all amounts
wrongfully obtained or retained by Defendants through the conduct alleged herein,
pursuant to 3 M.S.C. 1 8223 and the common law of unjust enrichment.

g. Order disgorgement of all ill-gotten gains obtained by Defendants through the
fraudulent and illegal acts alleged in this Complaint.

h. Enter declaratory judgment that Defendants conduct, as alleged herein, violated the
Mayflower RICO Act, 3 M.S.C. 1 8223, and other applicable laws.

i. Grant such other and further relief as the Court deems just, proper, and equitable to
redress and prevent the recurrence of the conduct alleged herein.

meowiitten 2025-09-21 02:37 p.m.
People v. Ernst & Young LLP, 114 AD3d 569, 570 (1st Dep't 2014) (citing N.Y. Exec. Law 63(12)):
[W]here, as here, there is a claim based on fraudulent activity, disgorgement may be available as an equitable remedy, notwithstanding the absence of loss to individuals or independent claims for restitution Disgorgement is distinct from the remedy of restitution because it focuses on the gain to the wrongdoer as opposed to the loss to the victim. Thus, disgorgement aims to deter wrongdoing by preventing the wrongdoer from retaining ill gotten gains from fraudulent conduct. Accordingly, the remedy of disgorgement does not require a showing or allegation of direct losses to consumers or the public; the source of the ill-gotten gains is immaterial.
See also People v. Amazon.com, Inc., 550 F Supp 3d 122, 130 (S.D.N.Y. 2021) ("the Attorney General can seek disgorgement of profits on the State's behalf").
